SUMMARIZER="A">      
 
West Germany has joined France in a ban on British beef imports due to
concern over "mad cow disease" (bovine spongiform encephalopathy or
BSE). Despite assurances from the British government that the beef is
safe, some are skeptical and the price of British beef is
dropping. British officials believe that France and West Germany
imposed the bans to protect their domestic sales. European Community
commissioners have also protested the import ban. On May 11 it was
reported that a Siamese cat had died from a form of BSE and the press
went wild suggesting that if cats can get it people can too.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d05"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910107-0139"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="A">    
 
About 20,000 British cattle have been destroyed since 1986 in hopes of
eradicating bovine spongiform encephalopathy ( BSE or "mad cow"
disease). The similarity of human and animal forms of spongiform
encephalopathy has raised the question whether people catch it from
animals. An outbreak of the human form (Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease or
CJD) in a sheep-herding part of Slovakia where the ovine form
(scrapie) was present seemed to suggest a connection. Latest research,
however, seems to suggest that the disease is caused by an altered
protein (prion) in the brain and is probably spread by consumption of
tissue infected with expanding prion.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d05"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT921-9310"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="A">  

"Mad cow disease" (bovine spongiform encephalopathy or BSE), has been
found in Britain's sparsely scattered antelope population, including
elands, kuru and an Arabian oryx. In all, six species other than
cattle have been confirmed with the disease over the past three
years. There has also been a pronounced increase in the number of
sheep affected by the ovine form of the disease ("scrapie") with 894
cases diagnosed in 1991 compared to just 348 in 1990. Since 1989 the
condition has been confirmed in 23 cats and 29 goats. There is not
sufficient data to conclude how the disease is spread.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d05"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT931-3883"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="A">       
 
British government experts reassured the public yesterday that it is
safe to eat beef and that there is no scientific evidence of a causal
link between "mad cow" disease (bovine spongiform encephalopathy or
BSE) and human Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease (CJD). Anxiety had been
raised by news that a dairy farmer whose herd had a case of BSE in
1989 died last year of CJD. Both diseases are caused by particles of
infectious protein called prions. There has been no change in the
incidence of CJD, however, while the incidence of BSE has continued to
grow.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d05"
TYPE="PERDOC"
